x4freetext: Oak Ridge Isochronous Cyclotron.
Momentum Analyzed in a 153 Degree Magnet.
Monoenergetic 28.8 +/- 0.1 and 61.5+/-0.1 MeV Protons,
Focused on the Target in a Spot of Approximately
8 mm Diameter, with a Walk of +/- 0.4 Cm.
The Secondary Particle Type was Identified with
A Combination of Delta-E Versus E and Flight-
Time Versus E, Which Permitted Unambiguous
Identification from a Few MeV Up to 62 MeV.
The Low-Energy Cutoffs For the Different Particles were
61.5 MeV
Protons                3.6 MeV
Deuterons              4.9 MeV
Tritons                6.4 MeV
Helium-3              12.6 MeV
Alphas                12.5 MeV
28.8 MeV
Protons                3.6 MeV
Deuterons              4.8 MeV
Tritons                6.4 MeV
Helium-3              12.5 MeV
Alphas                12.3 MeV
A Solid State Three-Detector
Telescope, with Two Silicon Delta-E Detectors and a
Lithium-Drifted Germanium Detector Used For Total
Energy Absorption. The Total Resolution was
Approximately 200 KeV For Most of the Data.
For  Some  Data the Resolution was 400 - 500 KeV Due to
Detector Failure.
The Telescope was Shielded by Tantalum Collimators,
With Thicknesses of 0.432 Cm and 0.013 Cm at the 61.5
And 28.8 MeV Runs, Respectively. The Area of the
Collimators was 0.522 Cm2 +/- 1.5 %. The
Distance from the Target to the Collimators was 45.8
Cm +/- 1 %. The Collimator had a Misalignment
At the Center of the Scattering Chamber of +/- 0.5 Cm.
The Precision of the Detector Angle was +/- 0.5
Degrees.
The Zero Angle was Determined to +/- 0.5 Degrees.
The Angular Resolution was +/- 1.2 Degrees.
.The Sample was a Commercial Gold Foil, with a Thick-
Ness of 7.02 +/- 0.07 Mg/Cm2 and a Nonunuformity of
+/- 1.5 %. The Sample had a Copper Contaminant
Of 0.2 Mole-%.
.The Data were Corrected For
1. Nuclear Reactions in the Germanium Detector,
2. Collimator Edge Penetration,
3. Dead Layer in the Path of the Scattered Particles,
4. Multiple Scattering of Particles in the First Two
Detectors, Which Made Them Miss the Total
Absorption Detector, and
5. Energy Loss of the Secondary Particles in the
Target.
Statistical Error in Data.
Systematic Error in Data, with Contributions
Such As
1. Uncertainty in Various Corrections  +/- 2 %
2. Uncertainty in Number of Protons
Striking the Target                 +/- 1 %
3. Uncertainty in Dead Time            +/- 1.5 %
Uncertainty of Beam Energy.
The Uncertainty in Number of  Protons  Striking
The Target was +/- 1 %.
.Data Taken from Main Reference by N.O.
N.O.
Correction For Bib Sections were Included
by
F.C.
Reaction Lines are Corrected.
Last checking has been done.
DATE is corrected
